io.multimap

Class Iterator

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.multimap.Iterator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AutoCloseable

    public class Iterator
extends Object
implements AutoCloseable
    An iterator that reads a list of values, possibly by streaming them from an external device. Objects of this class hold a reader lock on the associated list so that multiple threads can iterate the same list at the same time, but no thread can modify it. If an instance is not needed anymore close() must be called in order to release the reader lock. Not closing an iterator leaves the underlying list in locked state which leads to deadlocks sooner or later.

    In contrast to the standard Iterator interface, this class has the following properties:

    • Lazy initialization. The iterator does not perform any I/O operation until a value is actually requested via next(), nextAsByteArray(), peekNext(), or peekNextAsByteArray(). This might be useful in cases where multiple iterators have to be collected first in order to decide in which order they need to be processed.
    • The iterator can tell the number of remaining values via available().
    • The iterator can emit the next value without moving forward via peekNext() or peekNextAsByteArray().
    Author:
    Martin Trenkmann

    • Method Detail

      • available

        public long available()
        Returns the remaining number of values to be iterated. Calling this method does not trigger any I/O operation.

      • hasNext

        public boolean hasNext()
        Returns true if the iterator has more values, false otherwise.

      • next

        public ByteBuffer next()
        Returns the next value from the underlying list and moves the iterator once forward. The returned ByteBuffer is a direct one, i.e. it wraps a pointer to native allocated memory not managed by the Java Garbage Collector. This pointer is only valid as long as the iterator does not move forward. Therefore, the buffer should only be used to immediately parse the original data out of it. Most serialization libraries should be able to consume this kind of buffer. If a byte array is required or an independent copy of the value nextAsByteArray() should be used instead.

      • nextAsByteArray

        public byte[] nextAsByteArray()
        Same as before, but returns the next value as byte array. Internally calls next() and copies the content of the byte buffer into a newly allocated byte array. Since that byte array is managed by the Java Garbage Collector it can be copied around or stored in a collection as any other Java object, in contrast to the original byte buffer.

      • peekNext

        public ByteBuffer peekNext()
        Same as next(), but does not move the iterator once forward.

      • peekNextAsByteArray

        public byte[] peekNextAsByteArray()
        Same as nextAsByteArray(), but does not move the iterator once forward.

      • close

        public void close()
        Closes the iterator and releases native resources such as locks. An iterator must be closed if no longer needed in order to avoid deadlocks.
        Specified by:
        close in interface AutoCloseable
